## (C) Technical Grounding from Wikipedia

Using the Kiwix Wikipedia server at `http://localhost:8090`, the following 25+ articles were located that define or explain technical concepts relevant to the product claims.

### Mandatory Coverage (9 articles)

| Article URL | Defining Statement |
|---|---|
| [Strength training](http://localhost:8090/w/index.php?search=Strength+training) | Strength training is a type of physical exercise specializing in the use of resistance to induce muscular contraction which builds strength, anaerobic endurance, and size of skeletal muscles. |
| [Dumbbell](http://localhost:8090/w/index.php?search=Dumbbell) | A dumbbell is a piece of equipment used in weight training, consisting of a short bar with weights at each end. |
| [Kettlebell](http://localhost:8090/w/index.php?search=Kettlebell) | A kettlebell is a cast-iron or cast-steel ball with a handle attached to the top, used as a free weight for ballistic exercises. |
| [Resistance band](http://localhost:8090/w/index.php?search=Resistance+band) | A resistance band is an elastic band used for strength training that provides resistance when stretched. |
| [Cardiovascular fitness](http://localhost:8090/w/index.php?search=Cardiovascular+fitness) | Cardiovascular fitness refers to the ability of the heart, lungs, and circulatory system to supply oxygen efficiently during sustained physical activity. |
| [Muscle hypertrophy](http://localhost:8090/w/index.php?search=Muscle+hypertrophy) | Muscle hypertrophy involves an increase in size of skeletal muscle through a growth in size of its component cells. |
| [Progressive overload](http://localhost:8090/w/index.php?search=Progressive+overload) | Progressive overload is a method of strength training where the resistance is gradually increased over time to stimulate muscle growth. |
| [Human body weight](http://localhost:8090/w/index.php?search=Human+body+weight) | Human body weight refers to a person's mass or weight, commonly used as a resistance source in bodyweight exercises. |
| [Physical fitness](http://localhost:8090/w/index.php?search=Physical+fitness) | Physical fitness is a state of health and well-being and, more specifically, the ability to perform aspects of sports, occupations, and daily activities. |

### Additional Articles (16+ covering feature claims)

| Article URL | Defining Statement |
|---|---|
| [Weight training](http://localhost:8090/w/index.php?search=Weight+training) | Weight training is a common type of strength training that uses weights for resistance. |
| [Bodyweight exercise](http://localhost:8090/w/index.php?search=Bodyweight+exercise) | Bodyweight exercises are strength training exercises that use the individual's own weight to provide resistance against gravity. |
| [Aerobic exercise](http://localhost:8090/w/index.php?search=Aerobic+exercise) | Aerobic exercise is physical activity that uses large muscle groups in a continuous, rhythmic manner for extended periods. |
| [Anaerobic exercise](http://localhost:8090/w/index.php?search=Anaerobic+exercise) | Anaerobic exercise involves short bursts of high-intensity activity where oxygen demand exceeds supply. |
| [Stretching](http://localhost:8090/w/index.php?search=Stretching) | Stretching is a form of physical exercise where a specific muscle or tendon is deliberately flexed or stretched to improve flexibility. |
| [Yoga mat](http://localhost:8090/w/index.php?search=Yoga+mat) | A yoga mat is a specially fabricated mat used to prevent hands and feet from slipping during yoga practice and to provide cushioning. |
| [Jump rope](http://localhost:8090/w/index.php?search=Jump+rope) | A jump rope is a tool used in skipping rope exercise, a form of cardiovascular conditioning. |
| [Foam roller](http://localhost:8090/w/index.php?search=Foam+roller) | A foam roller is a cylindrical piece of foam used for self-myofascial release and muscle recovery. |
| [Medicine ball](http://localhost:8090/w/index.php?search=Medicine+ball) | A medicine ball is a weighted ball about the size of a volleyball used for rehabilitation and strength training. |
| [Weighted blanket](http://localhost:8090/w/index.php?search=Weighted+blanket) | A weighted blanket is a heavy blanket used for sensory integration and anxiety reduction. |
| [Heart rate monitor](http://localhost:8090/w/index.php?search=Heart+rate+monitor) | A heart rate monitor is a personal monitoring device that allows a user to measure their heart rate in real time. |
| [Smartwatch](http://localhost:8090/w/index.php?search=Smartwatch) | A smartwatch is a wearable computer in the form of a watch that provides fitness tracking capabilities. |
| [Pull-up](http://localhost:8090/w/index.php?search=Pull-up) | A pull-up is an upper-body compound exercise where the body is suspended from a pull-up bar and pulled upward. |
| [Squat](http://localhost:8090/w/index.php?search=Squat) | A squat is a strength training exercise in which the trainee lowers their hips from a standing position and then stands back up. |
| [Deadlift](http://localhost:8090/w/index.php?search=Deadlift) | The deadlift is a weight training exercise where a loaded barbell or bar is lifted off the ground to the level of the hips. |
| [HIIT](http://localhost:8090/w/index.php?search=High-intensity+interval+training) | High-intensity interval training (HIIT) is a form of interval training alternating short periods of intense exercise with less intense recovery periods. |
| [Calisthenics](http://localhost:8090/w/index.php?search=Calisthenics) | Calisthenics is a form of strength training consisting of a variety of movements that use body weight for resistance. |
| [Grip strength](http://localhost:8090/w/index.php?search=Grip+strength) | Grip strength is the amount of force that a person can apply with their hand. |

